  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to Soyou's Rhyme, Sent Separately
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To hold oneself together, one barely manages three meager things.
    Living in the world is truly like stealing a single glimpse.
    When talent runs dry, in dreams I grope for the brush within my breast.
    As spring departs, day by day the face in the mirror grows lined.
    The thatched cottage vainly settles by mountain streams, east and west.
    My words, like mountains great and small, inspire only shame.
    Few among our circle know one like you.
    Snow-laden carts and ice-built pillars—these we must climb together.
  footnotes:
    - The poem uses the metaphor of 'stealing a glimpse' to express the limited perspective and fleeting nature of human existence
    - The 'brush within my breast' refers to one's inner poetic capacity and creative spirit
    - References to 'great and small mountains' likely allude to other poets or literary traditions, expressing humble self-assessment
    - The closing image of 'snow carts and ice pillars' suggests shared hardship and mutual support among kindred spirits
